<br>
&quot;Prisoners of war shall be subject to the laws, regulations, and orders in force in the army of the State into whose hands they have fallen.&quot;<br>
<br>
This means the US Uniform Code of Military Justice applies, not the US Constitution.  <br>
<br>
Throughout history, prisoners of war are typically held until the war is over, at which point they are repatriated.  An exception would apply if the POW was considered a war criminal.  They would be held until a war tribunal was conducted.    As long as the US &quot;war on terror&quot; is going on, these Al-Qaeda prisoners will be kept locked up.  To release them prematurely would be assinine.  They would just go back to their terrorist ways.  If any are tried for war crimes, it won't be in the US either.  Most likely it would be in The Hague, where most international war criminals are tried. <p>Kebkin <!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><br>
