</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kebkin>Kebkin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 38<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/9/03 2:10:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=282.topic&index=26>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: National security or freedom for terrorists?</span><hr size=1> Moussaoui is being tried in US courts for his alleged involvement in the 9/11 attacks.  He is being tried as a criminal.  The Bill of Rights should apply but for reasons discussed in the linked article, the government is witholding information for national security reasons.  I'm no legal expert, but I see the Supreme Court eventually getting involved here because of this.  <br>
<br>
The detainees in Gitmo are members of the Taliban or Al-Qaeda captured during the war in Afghanistan.  These guys are POWs.  If they are put to trial, it will be as a war criminals.  <br>
<br>
After the 9/11 attacks, there were countless articles written about how personal freedoms/rights guaranteed in the Bill of Rights would be temporarily challenged as we waged the war on terror.  Some people (liberals and libertarians if you want to stereotype) are obviously opposed to this.  The thing is, throughtout history, during times of war, its been a common practice to limit personal freedoms/rights due to national security reasons.  One of the best examples in US history is when Lincoln declared martial law in Maryland to prevent them from seceding and suspended the writ of habeus corpus.  In hindsight, Lincoln did the right thing.  At the time though he was highly criticized.<br>
<br>
Only time will tell if the Bush administration is pursuing the correct course of action in the war on terror.  When the war on terror has been won, then I expect our personal freedoms/rights to return to the state they were in prior to 9/11.  If they aren't, then I'll be right there next to the liberals and libertarians voicing my dissent.<br>
<br>
